{"title_page": "Snowflake (airline)", "text_new": "{{POV check|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Airline\n| airline        = Snowflake\n| logo           = File:SAS Snowflake logo.svg\n| logo_size      =\n| IATA           = SK\n| ICAO           = SAS\n| callsign       = Scandinavian\n| parent         = [[SAS Group]]\n| founded        =\n| commenced      = 19 March 2003\n| ceased         = 31 October 2004\n| bases          = <div>\n*[[Copenhagen Airport]]\n*[[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]</div>\n| focus_cities   =\n| frequent_flyer = [[Eurobonus]]\n| alliance       =\n| fleet_size     = 4\n| destinations   = 28\n| headquarters   = [[SAS Fr\u00f6sundavik Office Building]], [[Solna Municipality]], [[Sweden]]\n| key_people     =\n| website        = [https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.flysnowflake.com flysnowflake.com]\n}}\n\n'''Snowflake''' was a [[low-cost airline]] that operated out of [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]], and [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] between 30 March 2003 and 30 October 2004. Owned by the [[SAS Group]], it was organized as a [[business unit]] within [[Scandinavian Airlines]], operating as a [[virtual airline (economics)|virtual airline]] using their crew and aircraft. Snowflake served a total 28 destinations from its bases at [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]] and [[Copenhagen Airport]].\n\nThe concept was launched using four [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] aircraft. It mainly served Mediterranean holiday destinations, as well as destinations popular with expatriates. From March 2004 two 737 aircraft were replaced with two [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]s. The airline underestimated its costs and achieved an insufficient [[load factor (aeronautics)|load factor]], thus making services unprofitable. After operations ended, SAS continued to use ''Snowflake'' as a brand for discounted tickets to European destinations.\n\n==History==\nIn 2003 SAS underwent a major restructuring program, which largely focused on reducing [[unit cost]]s. As part of the program, the company's management, in cooperation with [[McKinsey & Company]] devised a scheme to better target the leisure market. The models of [[Ryanair]] and SAS' partner airline [[Lufthansa]]'s low-cost subsidiary [[Germanwings]] were examined. SAS had just bought its main Norwegian competitor, [[Braathens]], and had also significantly reduced Swedish domestic competition through the purchase of [[Linjeflyg]]. The airline was worried about new entrants in these markets, in particular about Ryanair and [[EasyJet]].<ref name=bjornelid>{{cite book |title=SAS \u2013 om konsten att s\u00e4nka ett flygbolag |last=Bj\u00f6rnelid |first=Richard |publisher=Atlas |location=Stockholm |year=2011 |isbn=978-91-7389-396-1 |language=Swedish |pages=244\u2013248}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boeing 737-883, Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0383454.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport]]]]\nThe SAS Group announced plans for the airline on 10 December 2002, at the time giving it the provisional name ''Scandinavian Light''. The company stated that they aimed to create a low-cost airline which would focus on the leisure holiday market and on Mediterranean destinations. SAS hoped that the new airline would target a different market than Scandinavian Airlines and that the latter could instead focus on the business. A challenge for the company was at the time that it had overcapacity after a recent drop in passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS planerar l\u00e5gprissatsning |agency=[[Tidningarnas Telegrambyr\u00e5]] |date=10 December 2002 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Snowflake'' brand was announced on 19 March 2003 and services commenced on 30 March.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/resa/flyg/article10351145.ab |title=Sn\u00f6flinga ska lyfta SAS ekonomi |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |date=19 March 2003 |language=Swedish |accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> Four Boeing 737-800 were transferred to the new airline and painted in a new livery. Two were stationed at Stockholm Arlanda Airport and two at Copenhagen Airport. SAS chose not to launch the service in Norway. It considered the newly-formed [[SAS Braathens]] to be a lost-cost carrier and did not see the need for differentiation in the Norwegian market.<ref name=bjornelid /> Ticket prices started at 279 [[Swedish krona]] (SEK) and 295 [[Danish kroner]] (DKK) plus taxes. About ten seats per departure were sold at that price.<ref name=superrea>{{cite news |title=Super-rea p\u00e5 nya flygresor. \u00c5k till Medelhavet f\u00f6r bara 279 kronor |last=Holmgren |first=Hasse |work=[[Expressen]] |date=19 December 2002 |page=10 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Snowflake 737-883.jpg|thumb|left|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Prague Ruzyn\u011b Airport]]]]\nThe first services were from Stockholm to [[Alicante]], [[Athens]], [[Barcelona]], [[Bologna]], [[Budapest]], [[Dublin]], [[Istanbul]], [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Nice]], [[Prague]] and [[Rome]]. From Copenhagen the airline's first flights were to Alicante, Athens, Bologna, [[Lisbon]], M\u00e1laga, [[Palma de Mallorca]], [[Pristina]] and [[Sarajevo]]. The latter two were particularly aimed at expatriates, rather than tourists.<ref name=superrea /> By May the airline had achieved a [[passenger load factor|load factor]] of seventy percent,<ref>{{cite news |title=Folks r\u00e4dsla ny sm\u00e4ll f\u00f6r SAS |last=Pedersen |first=Hermod |work=[[Sydsvenskan]] |date=10 May 2003 |page=13 |language=Swedish}}</ref> increasing to eighty-two percent by September.<ref name=expands>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031106-snowflakeS04-eng.pdf |title=snowflake expands the coming summer |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=6 November 2003 |format=PDF |accessdate=20 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040620104926/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031106-snowflakeS04-eng.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref> Snowflake then announced three new destinations from Stockholm from the start of the winter program in October: [[Lyon]], [[Beograd]] and [[Beirut]]. The latter two were mainly aimed at expatriates.<ref name=lyon>{{cite news |title=Snowflake \u00e4ven till Lyon och Beirut |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=18 May 2003 |page=56 |language=Swedish}}</ref> A new fare scheme was introduced from 1 October, whereby there were eight price levels, ranging from \u20ac58 to \u20ac228. It also started offering discounted booking fees for tickets bought online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031002-snowflake_booking_eng.pdf |title=Worldwide booking and ticketless travel with snowflake |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=2 October 2003 |format=PDF |accessdate=19 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040619151529/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031002-snowflake_booking_eng.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref> In November Snowflake announced that it would end services to Dublin and Barcelona, citing low profitability. Scandinavian Airlines started to serving Dublin itself.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake skippar Barcelona |last=Nilsson |first=Hanna |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |date=9 November 2003 |page=33 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (DC-9-82), Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0923990.jpg|thumb|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Z\u00fcrich Airport]]]]\nSnowflake was hit by a strike within the SAS Group starting on 1 February 2004 amongst ground handlers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fortsatt flygstrejk med 85 inst\u00e4llda avg\u00e5ngar |work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]] |date=2 February 2004 |page=21 |language=Swedish}}</ref> From February Snowflake introduced services from Stockholm to [[Bilbao]] and [[Olbia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake \u00f6ppnar Bilbaolinje |work=[[Bor\u00e5s Tidning]] |date=16 February 2004 |page=9 |language=Swedish}}</ref> Starting with the 2004 summer schedule, commencing 28 March, SAS introduced additional services. From Copenhagen the airline started flights to [[Ankara]], Beirut, [[Skopje]], [[Split, Croatia|Split]] and [[Valletta]]. From Stockholm services were introduced to Ankara, [[Inverness]], Lisbon, Palma de Mallorca, Split, Skope and Valletta.<ref name=expands /> At the same time two more aircraft, 156-seat McDonnell Douglas MD-82s, were introduced to the Snowflake fleet.<ref name=planespotters>{{cite web |url=http://www.planespotters.net/Airline/Snowflake |title=Snowflake Fleet Details and History |publisher=Planespotters |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2004 the load factor drop to forty percent. Snowflake announced large cutbacks to the winter schedule, and planned to only operate four services: to Athens, Istanbul, Nice and Rome. This was down from thirteen during the previous winter season. With two flights each per week, this resulted in a very low fleet utilization rate. Snowflake had originally had success with their expatriate routes, but from 2004 passenger numbers fluctuated significantly on those routes.<ref name=tvingar>{{cite news |title=Katastrofsiffror tvingar SAS att banta l\u00e5gprisflyg |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]  |date=6 June 2004 |page=42 |language=Swedish}}</ref>  Similar cuts were carried out in Copenhagen: services were reduced to ten per week. This included the announcement of a new destination \u2013 [[Cairo]].<ref name=tvingar /> Two services, to Dublin and Prague, were taken over from Stockholm by Scandinavian Airlines. A further four destinations were cut with the winter program.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c5tta linjer ryker n\u00e4r Snowflake h\u00e5rdbantar |last=Hus\u00e5r |first=Malin |date=2 June 2004 |page=30 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |language=Swedish}}</ref> All services to Spain were taken over by [[Spanair]], which at the time was also owned by the SAS Group.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS ers\u00e4tter Snowflake med Spanair|last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=12 June 2004 |page=46 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SAS snowflake.JPG|thumb|left|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Alicante Airport]]]]\nThe load factor increased to eighty percent during the summer months. SAS announced on 18 August 2004 that it would terminate Snowflake services with effect 30 October. ''Snowflake'' would continue to exist as a brand name for discount tickets to European destinations.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS l\u00e4gger ner sitt l\u00e5gprisbolag |last=Grensund |first=Peter |date=18 August 2004 |page=24 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nSnowflake's business model was not the same as that of Scandinavian Airlines.  Snowflake was organized as a business unit with in SAS Group, in the same manner as Scandinavian Airlines. The airline was thereby just a brand employed for particular services. The aircraft operated with Scandinavian Airlines' aircraft, crew and codes. The two also shared management. Snowflake was organized to become an internal customer within the group, for instance purchasing ground services from [[SAS Ground Handling|SAS Ground Services]].<ref name=bjornelid />\n\nA key component to the operations was that the Snowflake services would be able to operate at a lower cost than the main airline. However, it soon proved that the company was not able to achieve the internal prices that were used in calculating costs. For instance, Snowflake incurred the same ground handling costs as Scandinavian Airlines. No discounts were therefore granted from SAS Ground Services or external ground handling providers. Similarly, if a Snowflake aircraft became sufficiently delayed, a conventional SAS aircraft would be dispatched instead.<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n[[File:Snowflake 737-800 LN-RPN.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Malta International Airport]]]]\nSnowflake was able to avoid many of the costs related to operating a [[spoke-hub distribution paradigm|network system]]. To begin with it operated only a single type of aircraft. These started and ended each day at their home base, avoiding accommodation costs for crews.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake f\u00e5r inte konkurrera med moderbolaget |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=30 July 2003 |page=32 |language=Swedish}}</ref> The Snowflake business unit employed only five people.<ref name=braconier>{{cite news |title=SAS har l\u00e4rt sig l\u00e5gprisl\u00e4xan |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=30 July 2003 |page=32 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nSnowflake incurred the same [[overhead cost]]s as Scandinavian; the lack of a clear separation between the airlines at an operational level meant that Snowflake never succeeded in lowering unit costs below that of Scandinavian Airlines. Finally, operating only four aircraft was too small a fleet to achieve the necessary [[economy of scale]]. With the ticket prices based on cost savings which never materialized, the airline failed to operate with a profit.<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n==Service==\nTickets were sold online and by telephone. They had a lower base price, additional services, including in-flight meals cost extra.<ref name=superrea /> Surcharges were also charged by travel agencies, which sold tickets for an interim period.  The airline only operated [[point-to-point transit|point-to-point]] services, rather than the network model used by Scandinavian Airline. Tickets were sold one-way and did not require a round trip and staying away over a Saturday to claim discounts. However, they did not support [[interlining]].<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (DC-9-82), Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0828974.jpg|thumb|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]]]\nStandard fare included one piece of checked-in luggage.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Baggage |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> The airline had a selection of in-flight meals, food and beverages for sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Food & beverages |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> Customers could redeem miles earned through SAS' loyalty program [[Eurobonus]], but miles could not be earned on flights with Snowflake. Snowflake services were popular for redemption because of the concentration of leisure destinations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=SAS Eurobonus |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\nThe airline initially operated a fleet of four [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]], with two aircraft based in Stockholm and two in Copenhagen.<ref name=bjornelid /> From March 2004 the two 737s in Copenhagen were replaced with two [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]].<ref name=planespotters /> All aircraft were owned and operated by Scandinavian Airlines, but retained a distinctive livery with a lemon-colored vertical stabilizer and otherwise white body. They had single-class seating in a more dense configuration than in SAS' conventional aircraft.<ref name=bjornelid /> All the aircraft were registered in Norway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/flottecie/Snowflake.htm |title=Snowflake fleet details |publisher=Airfleets |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ Snowflake fleet\n|-\n!scope=col | Aircraft\n!scope=col | Image\n!scope=col | Quantity\n!scope=col | Seating\n|-\n!scope=row | [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]]\n| [[File:Boeing 737-883, Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0551079.jpg|150px]] || 4 || 150<ref>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/19MAR2003.pdf |title=Snowflake towards southern climes |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=19 March 2003|format=PDF |accessdate=20 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040620103950/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/19MAR2003.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row | [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]\n| [[File:Snowflake MD-82.jpg|150px]] || 2 || 156<ref name=planespotters />\n|}\n\n==Destinations==\nSnowflake operated flights to a series of destinations from its bases in Copenhagen and Stockholm. They flew out of Terminal 2 at Copenhagen and Terminal 5 at Stockholm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Check-in and departure |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> Most flights had a limited frequency, typically one to four times per week. Flights operated to primary airports and not remote airports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flysnowflake.com/snowflake/where.asp |title=Where? |publisher=Snowflake |year=2003 |archivedate=13 April 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413190154/http://www.flysnowflake.com/snowflake/where.asp |accessdate=13 April 2003}}</ref> To avoid [[cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] customers from Scandinavian Airlines, Snowflake only flew to destinations not served by the other part of the group. This included several popular tourist destinations, such as [[London]] and [[Paris]], which also attracted a large share of business travelers.<ref name=braconier />\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ Snowflake destinations<ref name=superrea /><ref name=expands /><ref name=lyon />\n! scope=col | City\n! scope=col | Country\n! scope=col | Airport\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Alicante]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Alicante Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Ankara]]\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} Turkey || [[Esenbo\u011fa International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Athens]]\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} Greece || [[Athens International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Barcelona]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Beirut]]\n| {{flagicon|Lebanon}} Lebanon || [[Beirut\u2013Rafic Hariri International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Belgrade]]\n| {{flagicon|Serbia and Montenegro}} Serbia and Montenegro || [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Bilbao]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Bilbao Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Bologna]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Bologna Guglielmo Marconi Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Budapest]]\n| {{flagicon|Hungary}} Hungary || [[Budapest Ferenc Liszt International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Copenhagen]]\n| {{flagicon|Denmark}} Denmark || style=\"background-color: #D0E7FF\" | [[Copenhagen Airport]]<sup>[Base]</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Dublin]]\n| {{flagicon|Ireland}} Ireland || [[Dublin Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Inverness]]\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} United Kingdom || [[Inverness Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Istanbul]]\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} Turkey || [[Atat\u00fcrk International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Lisbon]]\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} Portugal || [[Lisbon Portela Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Lyon]]\n| {{flagicon|France}} France || [[Lyon\u2013Saint Exup\u00e9ry Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[M\u00e1laga]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[M\u00e1laga Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Nice]]\n| {{flagicon|France}} France || [[Nice C\u00f4te d'Azur Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Olbia]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Olbia Costa Smeralda Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Palma de Mallorca]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Palma de Mallorca Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Prague]]\n| {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} Czech Republic || [[V\u00e1clav Havel Airport Prague]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Pristina]]\n| {{flagicon|Serbia and Montenegro}} Serbia and Montenegro || [[Pristina International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Rome]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Leonardo da Vinci\u2013Fiumicino Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Sarajevo]]\n| {{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Bosnia and Herzegovina || [[Sarajevo International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Skopje]]\n| {{flagicon|Macedonia}} Macedonia || [[Skopje Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Split, Croatia|Split]]\n| {{flagicon|Croatia}} Croatia || [[Split Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Stockholm]]\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden || style=\"background-color: #D0E7FF\" | [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]<sup>[Base]</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Luqa]]\n| {{flagicon|Malta}} Malta || [[Malta International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Venice]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Venice Marco Polo Airport]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|SAS Snowflake}}\n\n{{SAS Group}}\n{{Airlines of Denmark}}\n{{Airlines of Sweden}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Denmark|Norway|Sweden}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snowflake (Airline)}}\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Airlines disestablished in 2004]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Defunct low-cost airlines]]\n[[Category:SAS Group]]\n[[Category:Scandinavian Airlines]]\n", "text_old": "{{POV check|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox Airline\n| airline        = Snowflake\n| logo           = File:SAS Snowflake logo.svg\n| logo_size      =\n| IATA           = SK\n| ICAO           = SAS\n| callsign       = Scandinavian\n| parent         = [[SAS Group]]\n| founded        =\n| commenced      = 19 March 2003\n| ceased         = 31 October 2004\n| bases          = <div>\n*[[Copenhagen Airport]]\n*[[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]</div>\n| focus_cities   =\n| frequent_flyer = [[Eurobonus]]\n| alliance       =\n| fleet_size     = 4\n| destinations   = 28\n| headquarters   = [[SAS Fr\u00f6sundavik Office Building]], [[Solna Municipality]], [[Sweden]]\n| key_people     =\n| website        = [https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.flysnowflake.com flysnowflake.com]\n}}\n\n'''Snowflake''' was a [[low-cost airline]] that operated out of [[Stockholm]], [[Sweden]], and [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] between 30 March 2003 and 30 October 2004. Owned by the [[SAS Group]], it was organized as a [[business unit]] within [[Scandinavian Airlines]], operating as a [[virtual airline (economics)|virtual airline]] using their crew and aircraft. Snowflake served a total 28 destinations from its bases at [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]] and [[Copenhagen Airport]].\n\nThe concept was launched using four [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] aircraft. It mainly served Mediterranean holiday destinations, as well as destinations popular with expatriates. From March 2004 two 737 aircraft were replaced with two [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]s. The airline underestimated its costs and achieved an insufficient [[load factor (aeronautics)|load factor]], thus making services unprofitable. After operations ended, SAS continued to use ''Snowflake'' as a brand for discounted tickets to European destinations.\n\n==History==\nIn 2003 SAS underwent a major restructuring program, which largely focused on reducing [[unit cost]]s. As part of the program, the company's management, in cooperation with [[McKinsey & Company]] devised a scheme to better target the leisure market. [[Ryanair]] and SAS' partner airline [[Lufthansa]]'s low-cost subsidiary [[Germanwings]] were models looked at. SAS had just bought its main Norwegian competitor, [[Braathens]], and had also significantly reduced Swedish domestic competition through the purchase of [[Linjeflyg]]. The airline was worried about new entrants in these markets, in particular about Ryanair and [[EasyJet]].<ref name=bjornelid>{{cite book |title=SAS \u2013 om konsten att s\u00e4nka ett flygbolag |last=Bj\u00f6rnelid |first=Richard |publisher=Atlas |location=Stockholm |year=2011 |isbn=978-91-7389-396-1 |language=Swedish |pages=244\u2013248}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boeing 737-883, Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0383454.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport]]]]\nThe SAS Group announced plans for the airline on 10 December 2002, at the time giving it the provisional name ''Scandinavian Light''. The company stated that they aimed to create a low-cost airline which would focus on the leisure holiday market and on Mediterranean destinations. SAS hoped that the new airline would target a different market than Scandinavian Airlines and that the latter could instead focus on the business. A challenge for the company was at the time that it had overcapacity after a recent drop in passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS planerar l\u00e5gprissatsning |agency=[[Tidningarnas Telegrambyr\u00e5]] |date=10 December 2002 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Snowflake'' brand was announced on 19 March 2003 and services commenced on 30 March.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/resa/flyg/article10351145.ab |title=Sn\u00f6flinga ska lyfta SAS ekonomi |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |date=19 March 2003 |language=Swedish |accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref> Four Boeing 737-800 were transferred to the new airline and painted in a new livery. Two were stationed at Stockholm Arlanda Airport and two at Copenhagen Airport. SAS chose not to launch the service in Norway. It considered the newly-formed [[SAS Braathens]] to be a lost-cost carrier and did not see the need for differentiation in the Norwegian market.<ref name=bjornelid /> Ticket prices started at 279 [[Swedish krona]] (SEK) and 295 [[Danish kroner]] (DKK) plus taxes. About ten seats per departure were sold at that price.<ref name=superrea>{{cite news |title=Super-rea p\u00e5 nya flygresor. \u00c5k till Medelhavet f\u00f6r bara 279 kronor |last=Holmgren |first=Hasse |work=[[Expressen]] |date=19 December 2002 |page=10 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Snowflake 737-883.jpg|thumb|left|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Prague Ruzyn\u011b Airport]]]]\nThe first services were from Stockholm to [[Alicante]], [[Athens]], [[Barcelona]], [[Bologna]], [[Budapest]], [[Dublin]], [[Istanbul]], [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Nice]], [[Prague]] and [[Rome]]. From Copenhagen the airline's first flights were to Alicante, Athens, Bologna, [[Lisbon]], M\u00e1laga, [[Palma de Mallorca]], [[Pristina]] and [[Sarajevo]]. The latter two were particularly aimed at expatriates, rather than tourists.<ref name=superrea /> By May the airline had achieved a [[passenger load factor|load factor]] of seventy percent,<ref>{{cite news |title=Folks r\u00e4dsla ny sm\u00e4ll f\u00f6r SAS |last=Pedersen |first=Hermod |work=[[Sydsvenskan]] |date=10 May 2003 |page=13 |language=Swedish}}</ref> increasing to eighty-two percent by September.<ref name=expands>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031106-snowflakeS04-eng.pdf |title=snowflake expands the coming summer |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=6 November 2003 |format=PDF |accessdate=20 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040620104926/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031106-snowflakeS04-eng.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref> Snowflake then announced three new destinations from Stockholm from the start of the winter program in October: [[Lyon]], [[Beograd]] and [[Beirut]]. The latter two were mainly aimed at expatriates.<ref name=lyon>{{cite news |title=Snowflake \u00e4ven till Lyon och Beirut |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=18 May 2003 |page=56 |language=Swedish}}</ref> A new fare scheme was introduced from 1 October, whereby there were eight price levels, ranging from \u20ac58 to \u20ac228. It also started offering discounted booking fees for tickets bought online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031002-snowflake_booking_eng.pdf |title=Worldwide booking and ticketless travel with snowflake |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=2 October 2003 |format=PDF |accessdate=19 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040619151529/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/PR031002-snowflake_booking_eng.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref> In November Snowflake announced that it would end services to Dublin and Barcelona, citing low profitability. Scandinavian Airlines started to serving Dublin itself.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake skippar Barcelona |last=Nilsson |first=Hanna |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |date=9 November 2003 |page=33 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (DC-9-82), Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0923990.jpg|thumb|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Z\u00fcrich Airport]]]]\nSnowflake was hit by a strike within the SAS Group starting on 1 February 2004 amongst ground handlers.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fortsatt flygstrejk med 85 inst\u00e4llda avg\u00e5ngar |work=[[G\u00f6teborgs-Posten]] |date=2 February 2004 |page=21 |language=Swedish}}</ref> From February Snowflake introduced services from Stockholm to [[Bilbao]] and [[Olbia]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake \u00f6ppnar Bilbaolinje |work=[[Bor\u00e5s Tidning]] |date=16 February 2004 |page=9 |language=Swedish}}</ref> Starting with the 2004 summer schedule, commencing 28 March, SAS introduced additional services. From Copenhagen the airline started flights to [[Ankara]], Beirut, [[Skopje]], [[Split, Croatia|Split]] and [[Valletta]]. From Stockholm services were introduced to Ankara, [[Inverness]], Lisbon, Palma de Mallorca, Split, Skope and Valletta.<ref name=expands /> At the same time two more aircraft, 156-seat McDonnell Douglas MD-82s, were introduced to the Snowflake fleet.<ref name=planespotters>{{cite web |url=http://www.planespotters.net/Airline/Snowflake |title=Snowflake Fleet Details and History |publisher=Planespotters |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2004 the load factor drop to forty percent. Snowflake announced large cutbacks to the winter schedule, and planned to only operate four services: to Athens, Istanbul, Nice and Rome. This was down from thirteen during the previous winter season. With two flights each per week, this resulted in a very low fleet utilization rate. Snowflake had originally had success with their expatriate routes, but from 2004 passenger numbers fluctuated significantly on those routes.<ref name=tvingar>{{cite news |title=Katastrofsiffror tvingar SAS att banta l\u00e5gprisflyg |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]]  |date=6 June 2004 |page=42 |language=Swedish}}</ref>  Similar cuts were carried out in Copenhagen: services were reduced to ten per week. This included the announcement of a new destination \u2013 [[Cairo]].<ref name=tvingar /> Two services, to Dublin and Prague, were taken over from Stockholm by Scandinavian Airlines. A further four destinations were cut with the winter program.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u00c5tta linjer ryker n\u00e4r Snowflake h\u00e5rdbantar |last=Hus\u00e5r |first=Malin |date=2 June 2004 |page=30 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |language=Swedish}}</ref> All services to Spain were taken over by [[Spanair]], which at the time was also owned by the SAS Group.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS ers\u00e4tter Snowflake med Spanair|last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=12 June 2004 |page=46 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n[[File:SAS snowflake.JPG|thumb|left|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Alicante Airport]]]]\nThe load factor increased to eighty percent during the summer months. SAS announced on 18 August 2004 that it would terminate Snowflake services with effect 30 October. ''Snowflake'' would continue to exist as a brand name for discount tickets to European destinations.<ref>{{cite news |title=SAS l\u00e4gger ner sitt l\u00e5gprisbolag |last=Grensund |first=Peter |date=18 August 2004 |page=24 |work=[[Aftonbladet]] |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\n==Operations==\nSnowflake's business model was not the same as that of Scandinavian Airlines.  Snowflake was organized as a business unit with in SAS Group, in the same manner as Scandinavian Airlines. The airline was thereby just a brand employed for particular services. The aircraft operated with Scandinavian Airlines' aircraft, crew and codes. The two also shared management. Snowflake was organized to become an internal customer within the group, for instance purchasing ground services from [[SAS Ground Handling|SAS Ground Services]].<ref name=bjornelid />\n\nA key component to the operations was that the Snowflake services would be able to operate at a lower cost than the main airline. However, it soon proved that the company was not able to achieve the internal prices that were used in calculating costs. For instance, Snowflake incurred the same ground handling costs as Scandinavian Airlines. No discounts were therefore granted from SAS Ground Services or external ground handling providers. Similarly, if a Snowflake aircraft became sufficiently delayed, a conventional SAS aircraft would be dispatched instead.<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n[[File:Snowflake 737-800 LN-RPN.jpg|thumb|[[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]] at [[Malta International Airport]]]]\nSnowflake was able to avoid many of the costs related to operating a [[spoke-hub distribution paradigm|network system]]. To begin with it operated only a single type of aircraft. These started and ended each day at their home base, avoiding accommodation costs for crews.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snowflake f\u00e5r inte konkurrera med moderbolaget |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=30 July 2003 |page=32 |language=Swedish}}</ref> The Snowflake business unit employed only five people.<ref name=braconier>{{cite news |title=SAS har l\u00e4rt sig l\u00e5gprisl\u00e4xan |last=Braconier |first=Fredrik |work=[[Svenska Dagbladet]] |date=30 July 2003 |page=32 |language=Swedish}}</ref>\n\nSnowflake incurred the same [[overhead cost]]s as Scandinavian; the lack of a clear separation between the airlines at an operational level meant that Snowflake never succeeded in lowering unit costs below that of Scandinavian Airlines. Finally, operating only four aircraft was too small a fleet to achieve the necessary [[economy of scale]]. With the ticket prices based on cost savings which never materialized, the airline failed to operate with a profit.<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n==Service==\nTickets were sold online and by telephone. They had a lower base price, additional services, including in-flight meals cost extra.<ref name=superrea /> Surcharges were also charged by travel agencies, which sold tickets for an interim period.  The airline only operated [[point-to-point transit|point-to-point]] services, rather than the network model used by Scandinavian Airline. Tickets were sold one-way and did not require a round trip and staying away over a Saturday to claim discounts. However, they did not support [[interlining]].<ref name=bjornelid />\n\n[[File:McDonnell Douglas MD-82 (DC-9-82), Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0828974.jpg|thumb|[[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]] at [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]]]\nStandard fare included one piece of checked-in luggage.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Baggage |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> The airline had a selection of in-flight meals, food and beverages for sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Food & beverages |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> Customers could redeem miles earned through SAS' loyalty program [[Eurobonus]], but miles could not be earned on flights with Snowflake. Snowflake services were popular for redemption because of the concentration of leisure destinations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=SAS Eurobonus |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet==\nThe airline initially operated a fleet of four [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]], with two aircraft based in Stockholm and two in Copenhagen.<ref name=bjornelid /> From March 2004 the two 737s in Copenhagen were replaced with two [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]].<ref name=planespotters /> All aircraft were owned and operated by Scandinavian Airlines, but retained a distinctive livery with a lemon-colored vertical stabilizer and otherwise white body. They had single-class seating in a more dense configuration than in SAS' conventional aircraft.<ref name=bjornelid /> All the aircraft were registered in Norway.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/flottecie/Snowflake.htm |title=Snowflake fleet details |publisher=Airfleets |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ Snowflake fleet\n|-\n!scope=col | Aircraft\n!scope=col | Image\n!scope=col | Quantity\n!scope=col | Seating\n|-\n!scope=row | [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|Boeing 737-800]]\n| [[File:Boeing 737-883, Snowflake (Scandinavian Airlines - SAS) AN0551079.jpg|150px]] || 4 || 150<ref>{{cite web |url=http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/19MAR2003.pdf |title=Snowflake towards southern climes |publisher=[[SAS Group]] |date=19 March 2003|format=PDF |accessdate=20 June 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040620103950/http://213.150.143.57/snowflake/en/about/pressreleases/19MAR2003.pdf |archivedate=20 June 2004}}</ref>\n|-\n!scope=row | [[McDonnell Douglas MD-80|McDonnell Douglas MD-82]]\n| [[File:Snowflake MD-82.jpg|150px]] || 2 || 156<ref name=planespotters />\n|}\n\n==Destinations==\nSnowflake operated flights to a series of destinations from its bases in Copenhagen and Stockholm. They flew out of Terminal 2 at Copenhagen and Terminal 5 at Stockholm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |title=Check-in and departure |publisher=Snowflake |year=2004 |archivedate=20 July 2004 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040720024640/http://snowflake.airkiosk.com/cgi-bin/airkiosk/I7/181002i2?SK&LANG=EN |accessdate=20 July 2004}}</ref> Most flights had a limited frequency, typically one to four times per week. Flights operated to primary airports and not remote airports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flysnowflake.com/snowflake/where.asp |title=Where? |publisher=Snowflake |year=2003 |archivedate=13 April 2003 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030413190154/http://www.flysnowflake.com/snowflake/where.asp |accessdate=13 April 2003}}</ref> To avoid [[cannibalization (marketing)|cannibalizing]] customers from Scandinavian Airlines, Snowflake only flew to destinations not served by the other part of the group. This included several popular tourist destinations, such as [[London]] and [[Paris]], which also attracted a large share of business travelers.<ref name=braconier />\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ Snowflake destinations<ref name=superrea /><ref name=expands /><ref name=lyon />\n! scope=col | City\n! scope=col | Country\n! scope=col | Airport\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Alicante]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Alicante Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Ankara]]\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} Turkey || [[Esenbo\u011fa International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Athens]]\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} Greece || [[Athens International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Barcelona]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Barcelona\u2013El Prat Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Beirut]]\n| {{flagicon|Lebanon}} Lebanon || [[Beirut\u2013Rafic Hariri International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Belgrade]]\n| {{flagicon|Serbia and Montenegro}} Serbia and Montenegro || [[Belgrade Nikola Tesla Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Bilbao]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Bilbao Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Bologna]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Bologna Guglielmo Marconi Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Budapest]]\n| {{flagicon|Hungary}} Hungary || [[Budapest Ferenc Liszt International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Copenhagen]]\n| {{flagicon|Denmark}} Denmark || style=\"background-color: #D0E7FF\" | [[Copenhagen Airport]]<sup>[Base]</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Dublin]]\n| {{flagicon|Ireland}} Ireland || [[Dublin Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Inverness]]\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} United Kingdom || [[Inverness Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Istanbul]]\n| {{flagicon|Turkey}} Turkey || [[Atat\u00fcrk International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Lisbon]]\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} Portugal || [[Lisbon Portela Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Lyon]]\n| {{flagicon|France}} France || [[Lyon\u2013Saint Exup\u00e9ry Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[M\u00e1laga]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[M\u00e1laga Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Nice]]\n| {{flagicon|France}} France || [[Nice C\u00f4te d'Azur Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Olbia]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Olbia Costa Smeralda Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Palma de Mallorca]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain || [[Palma de Mallorca Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Prague]]\n| {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} Czech Republic || [[V\u00e1clav Havel Airport Prague]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Pristina]]\n| {{flagicon|Serbia and Montenegro}} Serbia and Montenegro || [[Pristina International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Rome]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Leonardo da Vinci\u2013Fiumicino Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Sarajevo]]\n| {{flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} Bosnia and Herzegovina || [[Sarajevo International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Skopje]]\n| {{flagicon|Macedonia}} Macedonia || [[Skopje Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Split, Croatia|Split]]\n| {{flagicon|Croatia}} Croatia || [[Split Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Stockholm]]\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden || style=\"background-color: #D0E7FF\" | [[Stockholm Arlanda Airport]]<sup>[Base]</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Luqa]]\n| {{flagicon|Malta}} Malta || [[Malta International Airport]]\n|-\n! scope=row | [[Venice]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy || [[Venice Marco Polo Airport]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|SAS Snowflake}}\n\n{{SAS Group}}\n{{Airlines of Denmark}}\n{{Airlines of Sweden}}\n{{Portal bar|Aviation|Denmark|Norway|Sweden}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snowflake (Airline)}}\n[[Category:Airlines established in 2003]]\n[[Category:Airlines disestablished in 2004]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Defunct airlines of Sweden]]\n[[Category:Defunct low-cost airlines]]\n[[Category:SAS Group]]\n[[Category:Scandinavian Airlines]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snowflake_(airline)"}
{"title_page": "Bill Farmer", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|American voice actor and comedian (born 1952)}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Bill Farmer\n| image = 41st Annie Awards, Bill Farmer.jpg\n| caption = Farmer at the [[41st Annie Awards|2014 Annie Awards]]\n| birth_name = William Farmer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|11|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Pratt, Kansas]], U.S.\n| residence = [[San Fernando Valley, California]], U.S.<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/>\n| occupation = Voice actor, comedian\n| years_active = 1986\u2013present\n| alma_mater = [[University of Kansas]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Jennifer Farmer|1985}}<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy>{{cite web|last1=Stahl|first1=Scarlett|title=A Visit with a Goofy Guy Named Bill Farmer|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/News-ID514130.asp|publisher=LaughingPlace.com|accessdate=August 30, 2015|date=February 24, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307111604/http://www.laughingplace.com/News-ID514130.asp|archivedate=March 7, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| children = 1<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/><ref name=ToonhouseAbout />\n| agent = [http://www.voicebank.net/cabinet/agency.do?id=1591 AVO Talent]\n| website = {{url|http://www.billfarmer.net}}\n}}\n\n'''William Robert Farmer''' (born November 14, 1952) is an American voice actor and comedian. He has performed the voice of the [[Disney]] character [[Goofy]] since 1987, and is also the current voice of [[Pluto (Disney)|Pluto]] and [[Horace Horsecollar]].\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP sources section|BLP=yes|date=August 2015}}\nFarmer was born on November 14, 1952 in [[Pratt, Kansas]], as the second child in his family.<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/><ref name=D23BillFarmer>{{cite web|title=Disney Legends - Bill Farmer |url=https://d23.com/walt-disney-legend/bill-farmer/ |publisher=D23 |accessdate=August 30, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150830093555/https://d23.com/walt-disney-legend/bill-farmer/ |archivedate=August 30, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> His parents were of English and Welsh descent.<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/>\n\nFarmer's first job, at the age of 15, involved doing voices, especially those of [[Western (genre)|Western]] stars like [[John Wayne]] or [[Walter Brennan]]. He and his friends would sometimes go through fast food drive-thrus and order foods in his character voices.<ref name=\"BaltimoreSun1995\">{{cite news |last1=McTavish |first1=Brian |title=Bill Farmer is 'Goofy' for fun and profit |url=https://www.baltimoresun.com/news/bs-xpm-1995-05-04-1995124177-story.html |accessdate=August 24, 2019 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |date=May 4, 1995}}</ref> Bill graduated from the [[University of Kansas]] in 1975<ref name=\"BaltimoreSun1995\"/> and is a member of the Sigma Chi Fraternity. In college, he found work in radio and TV and then moved on to [[stand-up comedy]] as an impressionist until he moved out to [[Hollywood]], where he began voicing Goofy in January 1987.<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/> In 1982, while he was still doing stand-up comedy, Farmer worked at a comedy club called the Comedy Corner in [[Dallas, Texas]]. He continued to work there until his move to Hollywood in 1986.\n\nHis decision to move to California came from a Dallas commercial agent who suggested that, given his talent for voices, he should try his luck in California.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armstrong |first1=John |title=It's Goofy, but it's a job |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35290297/the_vancouver_sun/ |accessdate=August 26, 2019 |work=[[Vancouver Sun]] |date=September 7, 1995 |page=C3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{free access}}</ref> He was recently married, but he and his wife talked it over and came to an arrangement. She stayed back in Dallas while he commuted for a year after he got an apartment. Then four months after his moving out to Hollywood, his agent asked him if he could do any Disney characters.\n\nHe asserts that voice acting is not about funny voices, but about acting. His mentor was the versatile voice actor [[Daws Butler]], the man behind many of [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s characters. He taught Farmer that when doing cartoon voices, you're not merely doing a funny voice, you're an actor and the acting is premier and you have to think like the character you're doing.<ref name=\"Talkintoons\">{{cite web|url=http://techjives.net/2012/05/25/042-bill-farmer-on-talkin-toons-with-rob-paulsen-weekly-voice-acting-and-voice-over-tips/|title=042 \u2013 Bill Farmer on Talkin Toons with Rob Paulsen \u2013 Weekly Voice Acting and Voice Over Tips - Tech Jives Network|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources section|BLP=yes|date=August 2015}}\nIn 1987, Farmer had a small part as reporter Justin Ballard-Watkins in the film ''[[RoboCop]]''.<ref name=\"Talkintoons\" />\n\nHis very first voice over audition was for Goofy. When he auditioned for the voice, he studied the way the original actor [[Pinto Colvig]] performed as Goofy in the classic cartoons. He studied the hilarious laugh and the distinctive \"gawrsh\". He inherited the voice of Goofy (and also [[Pluto (Disney)|Pluto]])<ref name=ToonhouseAbout>{{cite web|title=About Toonhouse|url=http://www.toonhouseinc.com/about|publisher=Toonhouse Inc.|accessdate=August 30, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120423195851/http://www.toonhouseinc.com/about|archivedate=April 23, 2012}}</ref> around the same time [[Tony Anselmo]] inherited [[Donald Duck]] and [[Russi Taylor]] inherited [[Minnie Mouse]].\n\nHe originated the voice of [[Horace Horsecollar]] in Disney's version of ''[[The Prince and the Pauper (1990 film)|The Prince and the Pauper]]'' and has played him ever since as well.<ref name=\"Talkintoons\" /><ref name=\"Mediamikes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mediamikes.com/2014/02/disney-legend-bill-farmer-talks-about-voicing-goofy-and-new-series-the-7d/|title=Disney Legend, Bill Farmer talks about voicing Goofy and new Disney Junior series \"The 7D\"|author=|date=|work=mediamikes.com|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> Farmer also performed additional voices on ''[[The New Adventures of Mighty Mouse]]'' (1987) and ''[[Astro Boy (2003 TV series)|Astro Boy]]'' (2004).\n\nOther significant characters he has played include [[Yosemite Sam]], [[Sylvester (Looney Tunes)|Sylvester]] and [[Foghorn Leghorn]] in the movie ''[[Space Jam]]'' (1996). He has also done several guest voices, both on TV, including ''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]'' and in video games, including the [[Destroy All Humans! (series)|''Destroy All Humans!'' series]], [[Namco]]'s ''[[Tales of Symphonia]]'', where he voiced Governor-General Dorr, in [[Square Enix]]'s ''[[Kingdom Hearts]]'' series reprising the role of Goofy, Detective Date in the [[SEGA]] game [[Yakuza (video game)|''Yakuza'']], Captain Wedgewood and Frill Lizard in ''[[Ty the Tasmanian Tiger]]'', many voices on ''[[EverQuest II]]'', Cletus Samson, Floyd Sanders, Jeff Meyers and Ryan LaRosa in the video game ''[[Dead Rising]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voicechasers.com/database/showactor.php?actorid=1139|title=Bill Farmer|author=|date=|work=Voice Chasers|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref> and Sam and others in the cult classic adventure game ''[[Sam & Max Hit the Road]]''.\n\nFarmer has also played [[Secret Squirrel]] on ''[[Harvey Birdman, Attorney at Law]]'' in both the animated series and its spin-off video game, Stinkie in ''[[Casper: A Spirited Beginning]]'' and ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'', Willie Bear in ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]'', and [[Bugs Bunny]] and [[Daffy Duck]] in ''[[Robot Chicken]]''.\n\nFrom 2014 to 2016, he played Doc, the leader of the title characters in Disney's animated television series ''[[The 7D]]''.<ref name=\"Mediamikes\" />\n\nHe also voiced Blackhoof Boar Clan Leader in the 2008 video game ''[[Kung Fu Panda (video game)|Kung Fu Panda]]''.\n\nBill Farmer still regularly performs comedy routines at the [[Laugh Factory]].\n\nHe has been voicing the character \u201cHop-Pop\u201d on Disney's ''[[Amphibia (TV series)|Amphibia]]''.\n\n==Recognition==\nIn September 2009, Farmer was named a [[Disney Legend]]. In 2011, the International Family Film Festival awarded Bill Farmer the 'Friz Award' for Animation.\n\nHe won the [[Annie Award]] for Voice Acting in an Animated TV/Broadcast Production for his work as Goofy and Grandma Goofy in ''[[Mickey Mouse (TV series)|Mickey Mouse]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/01/annie-award-winners-2015-awards-winner-list-1201363829/|title=Annie Award Winners 2015: Full List Of Animation Award Winners - Deadline|author=Erik Pedersen|date=|work=Deadline|accessdate=28 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFarmer has been married to his wife Jennifer Farmer since 1985;<ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/> together they have a son.<ref name=ToonhouseAbout /><ref name=LPVisitGoofyGuy/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{More footnotes|section|BLP=yes|date=June 2015}}\n\n===Film===\n{|class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ List of voice roles in feature films\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Who Framed Roger Rabbit]]''\n| Additional voices\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=2011 Disneyana Fan Club Convention Highlight: Voice Panel|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zhpr84WzJLg|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=April 16, 2013|format=Video}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Rover Dangerfield]]''\n| Farm voices\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Beauty and the Beast (1991 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]''\n|Stanley\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 1995\n|''[[Theodore Rex (film)|Theodore Rex]]''\n| Additional voices\n|&nbsp;\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[A Goofy Movie]]''\n| [[Goofy]]\n| Nominated - [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Annie Award for Voice Acting by a Male Performer in an Animated Feature Production]]\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Toy Story]]''\n| Monotone Announcer\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Space Jam]]''\n| [[Foghorn Leghorn]], [[Sylvester (Looney Tunes)|Sylvester]], [[Yosemite Sam]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[The Hunchback of No