{"title_page": "Louisiana Territory (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1953 film directed by Harry W. Smith}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Louisiana Territory\n| image          = \n| alt            =\n| caption        = \n| film name      = \n| director       = Harry W. Smith<br>Peter Scoppa (assistant)\n| producer       = Jay Bonafield<br>Douglas Travers\n| writer         = Jerome Brondfield\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on |[title of the original work] |[writer of the original work]}} -->\n| starring       = \n| narrator       = \n| music          = [[George Bassman]]\n| cinematography = Harry W. Smith\n| editing        = Milton Sherman\n| studio         = [[RKO Pictures|RKO-Path\u00e9]]\n| distributor    = RKO Radio Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1953|10|14|Premiere-''New Orleans''|1953|10|16|''US''|  ref1= <ref name=AFI>{{cite web | url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=50921 | title=Louisiana Territory: Detail View | publisher=American Film Institute | accessdate= September 25, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402201904/http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=50921 | archivedate=April 2, 2014}}</ref>|ref2=<ref name=AFI />}}\n| runtime        = 65 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!-- Please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\" -->\n}}\n\n'''''Louisiana Territory''''' is a 1953 American [[historical drama|historical drama film]] directed by Harry W. Smith (who also photographed the film), from an original screenplay by Jerome Brondfield. It opens with the circumstances of the sale of the [[Louisiana Purchase|Louisiana Territory]] by [[Napoleon]]'s government and the roles of [[Robert R. Livingston (chancellor)|Robert Livingston]] and [[Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]]. However, most of the film deals with the spirit of Livingston visiting major cities of the territory decades later in 1953.<ref>description in 'Louisiana Territory (1953)' in IMDB https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0230469/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt</ref>\n\nProduced by [[RKO Pictures|RKO-Path\u00e9]], it was distributed by its sister company, RKO Radio Pictures, who premiered the film in [[New Orleans]] on October 14, 1953, with a national release two days later, on October 16. The film stars [[Val Winter]] as Livingston and Leo Zinser as Talleyrand. It also stars Julian Miester and Phyliss Massicot.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0230469}}\n\n[[Category:RKO Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:1950s 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n\n\n{{1950s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1953 film directed by Harry W. Smith}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Louisiana Territory\n| image          = \n| alt            =\n| caption        = \n| film name      = \n| director       = Harry W. Smith<br>Peter Scoppa (assistant)\n| producer       = Jay Bonafield<br>Douglas Travers\n| writer         = Jerome Brondfield\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on |[title of the original work] |[writer of the original work]}} -->\n| starring       = \n| narrator       = \n| music          = [[George Bassman]]\n| cinematography = Harry W. Smith\n| editing        = Milton Sherman\n| studio         = [[RKO Pictures|RKO-Path\u00e9]]\n| distributor    = RKO Radio Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|1953|10|14|Premiere-''New Orleans''|1953|10|16|''US''|  ref1= <ref name=AFI>{{cite web | url=http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=50921 | title=Louisiana Territory: Detail View | publisher=American Film Institute | accessdate= September 25, 2014 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402201904/http://www.afi.com/members/catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=50921 | archivedate=April 2, 2014}}</ref>|ref2=<ref name=AFI />}}\n| runtime        = 65 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!-- Please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\" -->\n}}\n\n'''''Louisiana Territory''''' is a 1953 American [[Historical period drama|historical drama film]] directed by Harry W. Smith (who also photographed the film), from an original screenplay by Jerome Brondfield. It opens with the circumstances of the sale of the [[Louisiana Purchase|Louisiana Territory]] by [[Napoleon]]'s government and the roles of [[Robert R. Livingston (chancellor)|Robert Livingston]] and [[Charles Maurice de Talleyrand-P\u00e9rigord]]. However, most of the film deals with the spirit of Livingston visiting major cities of the territory decades later in 1953.<ref>description in 'Louisiana Territory (1953)' in IMDB https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0230469/?ref_=ttpl_pl_tt</ref>\n\nProduced by [[RKO Pictures|RKO-Path\u00e9]], it was distributed by its sister company, RKO Radio Pictures, who premiered the film in [[New Orleans]] on October 14, 1953, with a national release two days later, on October 16. The film stars [[Val Winter]] as Livingston and Leo Zinser as Talleyrand. It also stars Julian Miester and Phyliss Massicot.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0230469}}\n\n[[Category:RKO Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:1950s drama films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:1950s 3D films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n\n{{1950s-drama-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kailash29792", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louisiana_Territory_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Final Flight", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{context|date=September 2017}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = Final Flight \n| image = Final Flight.jpg\n| caption = First edition\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Stephen Coonts]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| publisher     = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Techno-thriller novel]]\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]])\n| isbn =  0-385-24555-6  \n}}\n\n'''Final Flight''' is a 1988 novel by [[Stephen Coonts]].\n\n==Plot==\nJake \u201cCool Hand\u201d Grafton is now a CAG on a cruise in the Mediterranean. A group of terrorists kidnap some navy crew and learn how to penetrate the ship. Led by Qazi, they intend to steal nuclear bombs from the carrier. Meanwhile, Grafton deals with two accidents, leadership problems, and himself facing being grounded due to deteriorated night sight. An anti-terror-team led by Judith Farrell is after Qazi.\n\nThe terrorist successfully penetrate the ship during a port visit using uniform deception and helicopters. After taking the ship, with Admiral Parker as a hostage, they successfully load 6 nuclear weapons onto three helicopters.  The crew of the ship does not want them stolen and in independent actions, contrary to orders, they destroy two of the helicopters. One gets away with two devices and Kazhi on board. Grafton is the surviving senior officer after Admiral 'Cowboy' Parker, Captain James (CO of the ship), and the XO of the ship are killed. The Admiral commanding the Mediterranean fleet is hesitant to hunt the helicopter's that contain the nuclear weapons. Grafton disobeys him and pilots an F-14 hunting for the terrorists. He surmises that both weapons were transferred from the helicopters onto airplanes. He destroys the first aircraft, but the second aircraft is bound for Israel and has a fighter escort. He is able to down three of the six fighter aircraft and is trying to down the other transport aircraft containing the missing nuclear missile. Running out of missiles and with his cannon jammed, Grafton opts to ram his F-14 into the enemy aircraft.\n\nIn the end it is not clear if Grafton survives. The later novel The Minatour describes the events after Grafton rammed the aircraft.\n\n==Characters==\n*Jake \u201cCool Hand\u201d Grafton &ndash; Naval aviator, protagonist.\n*Robert \"Toad\" Tarkington; F-14 RIO. He appears later in a sequel novel.\n*\u201dCowboy\u201d Parker &ndash; Grafton's former squadron mate.  Now an admiral and commanding officer of the task force.\n*Reed; Grafton\u2019s navigator, he wanted to quit flying and died in an accident.\n*Callie &ndash; Grafton\u2019s wife.  They meet when Grafton tours [[Hong Kong]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Final Flight (Novel)}}\n[[Category:American thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Stephen Coonts]]\n[[Category:1986 American novels]]\n[[Category:Aviation novels]]\n\n\n{{1980s-thriller-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{context|date=September 2017}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n}}\n\n{{infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = Final Flight \n| image = Final Flight.jpg\n| caption = First edition\n| title_orig    = \n| translator    = \n| author        = [[Stephen Coonts]]\n| country       = [[United States]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| publisher     = [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]\n| series        = \n| genre         = [[Techno-thriller novel]]\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]])\n| isbn =  0-385-24555-6  \n}}\n\n'''Final Flight''' is a 1988 novel by [[Stephen Coonts]].\n\n==Plot==\nGrafton is now a CAG on a cruise in the Mediterranean. A group of terrorists kidnap some navy crew and learn how to penetrate the ship. Led by Qazi, they intend to steal nuclear bombs from the carrier. Meanwhile, Grafton deals with two accidents, leadership problems, and himself facing being grounded due to deteriorated night sight. An anti terror-team led by Judith Farrell is after Qazi.\n\nThe terrorist successfully penetrate the ship during a port visit using uniform deception and helicopters. After taking the ship, with Admiral Parker as a hostage, they successfully load 6 nuclear weapons onto three helicopters.  The crew of the ship does not want them stolen and in independent actions, contrary to orders, they destroy two of the helicopters. One gets away with two devices and Kazhi on board. Grafton is the surviving senior officer after Admiral 'Cowboy' Parker, Captain James (CO of the ship), and the XO of the ship are killed. The Admiral commanding the Mediterranean fleet is hesitant to hunt the helicopter's that contain the nuclear weapons. Grafton disobeys him and pilots an F-14 hunting for the terrorists. He surmises that both weapons were transferred from the helicopters onto airplanes. He destroys the first aircraft, but the second aircraft is bound for Israel and has a fighter escort. He is able to down three of the six fighter aircraft and is trying to down the other transport aircraft containing the missing nuclear missile. Running out of missiles and with his cannon jammed, Grafton opts to ram his F-14 into the enemy aircraft.\n\nIn the end it is not clear if Grafton survives. The later novel The Minatour describes the events after Grafton rammed the aircraft.\n\n==Characters==\n*Jake \u201cCool Hand\u201d Grafton &ndash; Naval aviator, protagonist.\n*Robert \"Toad\" Tarkington; F-14 RIO. He appears later in a sequel novel.\n*\u201dCowboy\u201d Parker &ndash; Grafton's former squadron mate.  Now an admiral and commanding officer of the task force.\n*Reed; Grafton\u2019s navigator, he wanted to quit flying and died in an accident.\n*Callie &ndash; Grafton\u2019s wife.  They meet when Grafton tours [[Hong Kong]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Final Flight (Novel)}}\n[[Category:American thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Stephen Coonts]]\n[[Category:1986 American novels]]\n[[Category:Aviation novels]]\n\n\n{{1980s-thriller-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jennifer T. Coen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Character's full name at opening of Plot paragraph for clarity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Final_Flight"}
